# UI Change Propagation Rule

When the user requests a visual or UI change, **apply it to every application** in the project
unless they explicitly say otherwise (e.g. "only in Gemini Studio", "just for the Tool Editor").

## What counts as a visual/UI change

- Colors, spacing, padding, margins, font sizes, font weights
- Border styles, border-radius, shadows, opacity
- Layout changes (flex direction, alignment, gaps)
- Animation/transition changes
- Node appearance (headers, bodies, handles, selection states)
- Toolbar/sidebar/dock appearance
- Controls, MiniMap, Background styling
- Context menus, dialogs, overlays, toasts
- Button styles, input field styles, dropdown styles

## Applications to update

1. **ShawnderMind** — `src/app/ideation/`
2. **Gemini Studio** — `src/app/gemini-studio/`
3. **Tool Editor** — `src/app/tool-editor/`
4. **Shared components** — `src/components/` (e.g. ImageContextMenu, Sidebar)
5. **Walter Storyboarding** — `tools/walter/src/` (extracted workspace package)
6. **Shared design tokens** — `packages/ui/src/tokens.css`
7. **Any future tool** added to `tools/*/`

## How to propagate

1. Identify the change and which CSS/component files it touches in the originating app.
2. Find the equivalent files in every other application.
3. Apply the same change everywhere, adapting class names but keeping values identical.
4. If the change belongs in `packages/ui/src/tokens.css` (e.g. a new token or token value change),
   update it there so all apps inherit automatically.
5. After applying, verify the build still passes.

## When NOT to propagate

- The user explicitly names a single app: "Change the Gemini Studio header to blue"
- The change is functionally app-specific (e.g. a node type unique to one canvas)
- The change is to logic/behavior, not visual appearance
